.TH "TILDR\-COMMANDS" "1" "2026" "Tildr" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
tildr\-commands \[em] command reference for Tildr
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]tildr\f[R] \f[I]<command>\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]]
[\f[I]target\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
This page documents all commands available in \f[B]tildr(1)\f[R].
.PP
The \f[B]add\f[R], \f[B]restore\f[R], and \f[B]unlink\f[R] commands
accept multiple file parameters simultaneously:
.IP
.EX
tildr add .config/nvim/init.vim .config/nvim/lua/plugins.lua
tildr restore .config/nvim/init.vim .config/nvim/lua/plugins.lua
.EE
.PP
If a path contains spaces, use single or double quotes:
.IP
.EX
tildr unlink \[aq].config/my app/config.toml\[aq] .config/nvim/init.vim
.EE
.SH PATH INPUT
Commands that receive files accept several equivalent HOME\-based paths:
.IP
.EX
tildr add .config/starship.toml
tildr add \[ti]/.config/starship.toml
tildr add $HOME/.config/starship.toml
.EE
.PP
Absolute paths inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] also work.
When your current directory is inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R], relative paths
are resolved from that directory when possible:
.IP
.EX
cd \[ti]/Documents
tildr add document.ods
tildr restore document.ods
.EE
.PP
The commands above are treated like
\f[CR]\[ti]/Documents/document.ods\f[R].
This applies to managed\-file commands such as \f[CR]add\f[R],
\f[CR]restore\f[R], \f[CR]unlink\f[R], \f[CR]cat\f[R], \f[CR]edit\f[R],
\f[CR]del\f[R], \f[CR]mv\f[R], and \f[CR]profile add/mv \-f\f[R].
.SH COMMANDS
.SS tildr init
Initializes the Tildr repository and writes the user configuration file.
.IP
.EX
tildr init
tildr init \-\-repo \[ti]/.dotfiles\-work
tildr init \-\-no\-git
tildr init \-\-force
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Options:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-r\f[R], \f[B]\[en]repo\f[R] \f[I]<PATH>\f[R]
Repository path, which must be inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\[en]no\-git\f[R]
Skip \f[CR]git init\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\[en]force\f[R]
Reinitialize even if config already exists.
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R], \f[B]\[en]quiet\f[R]
Suppress output.
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Creates the repository directory
.IP \[bu] 2
Writes \f[CR]\[ti]/.config/tildr/config.toml\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Detects whether Git is available in \f[CR]PATH\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Writes \f[CR][git].available\f[R] to the config
.IP \[bu] 2
Initializes a Git repository only when Git is available and
\f[CR]\-\-no\-git\f[R] is not used
.IP \[bu] 2
Refuses \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] itself as the repository root
.IP \[bu] 2
Refuses repositories outside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
If already initialized and \f[CR]\-\-force\f[R] is not passed, refreshes
the saved Git availability state
.SS tildr import
Clone a remote dotfiles repository and apply it.
.IP
.EX
tildr import https://github.com/user/dotfiles
tildr import https://github.com/user/dotfiles \[ti]/.dotfiles
tildr import https://github.com/user/dotfiles \-\-force
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Options:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-d\f[R], \f[B]\[en]dest\f[R] \f[I]<PATH>\f[R]
Local destination path (default: \f[CR]\[ti]/.dotfiles\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\[en]force\f[R]
Overwrite existing \f[CR]config.toml\f[R] if it points to a different
repo.
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\[en]dry\-run\f[R]
Show what would be done without making changes.
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R], \f[B]\[en]quiet\f[R]
Suppress output.
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Clones the Git repository to the specified destination (or
\f[CR]\[ti]/.dotfiles\f[R])
.IP \[bu] 2
Creates or updates \f[CR]\[ti]/.config/tildr/config.toml\f[R] with the
repository path
.IP \[bu] 2
Runs \f[CR]apply\f[R] automatically to establish symlinks
.IP \[bu] 2
Destination must be inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Refuses to overwrite a config pointing to a different repository unless
\f[CR]\-\-force\f[R] is used
.IP \[bu] 2
If a \f[CR].tildr/encrypted.gpg\f[R] bundle is present, decrypts
sensitive files after cloning
.SS tildr add
Adds a file or a directory tree from \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] into the
repository and replaces each file with a symlink.
.IP
.EX
tildr add .bashrc
tildr add .config/nvim
tildr add \[ti]/.config/starship.toml
tildr add $HOME/.config/starship.toml
tildr add .config/nvim/init.lua \-\-dry\-run
tildr add .bashrc .config/nvim/init.lua
tildr add .config/app01.json \-\-nolink
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Options:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\[en]dry\-run\f[R]
Preview actions without modifying files.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]nolink\f[R]
Add to repository without creating a symlink.
The file is added to \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R] automatically.
.TP
\f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\[en]force\f[R]
Remove an existing repository target before moving the file.
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R], \f[B]\[en]quiet\f[R]
Suppress output.
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
If no path is passed, Tildr opens a file picker to select a file from
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Files are moved into the repository
.IP \[bu] 2
Symlinks are created at the original home path
.IP \[bu] 2
With \f[CR]\-\-nolink\f[R], files are moved but no symlink is created
and the file is added to \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Directories are traversed recursively
.IP \[bu] 2
Paths matched by \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R] are skipped
.IP \[bu] 2
Already\-correct symlinks are skipped silently
.IP \[bu] 2
Existing sources in the target profile are preserved unless
\f[CR]\-\-force\f[R] is used
.IP \[bu] 2
Adding to an inactive profile stores the variant but keeps
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R] aligned with the active profile
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[CR]git.auto_commit = true\f[R], the repository is auto\-committed
after a successful run
.SS tildr apply
Applies repository state into \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] by creating or repairing
symlinks.
.IP
.EX
tildr apply
tildr apply \-\-check
tildr apply \-\-dry\-run
tildr apply \-\-force \-\-verbose
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Options:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\[en]check\f[R]
Verify that effective active\-profile files are correctly linked without
changing files.
Exits with a non\-zero status when a link is missing, broken, points to
the wrong source, conflicts with a regular file, or is unexpectedly left
from an inactive profile.
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\[en]dry\-run\f[R]
Preview actions.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R], \f[B]\[en]verbose\f[R]
Include unchanged or skipped entries in output.
.TP
\f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\[en]force\f[R]
Replace conflicting regular files or directories in \f[CR]$HOME\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R], \f[B]\[en]quiet\f[R]
Suppress output.
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Creates missing symlinks for all files effective for the active profile
.IP \[bu] 2
Repairs broken or incorrect symlinks automatically
.IP \[bu] 2
Removes Tildr\-owned symlinks for files that exist only in inactive
profiles
.IP \[bu] 2
Skips regular files already present in \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] unless
\f[CR]\-\-force\f[R] is used
.IP \[bu] 2
With \f[CR]\-\-check\f[R], only validates symlinks and reports missing,
broken, conflicting, or unexpected HOME links
.IP \[bu] 2
Uses the repository as the source of truth
.IP \[bu] 2
Does not modify repository content
.IP \[bu] 2
Always idempotent \[em] running multiple times produces the same result
.SS tildr clean
Removes empty directories left inside profile storage.
.IP
.EX
tildr clean
tildr clean \-\-dry\-run
tildr clean \-\-quiet
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Options:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\[en]dry\-run\f[R]
Preview directories that would be removed.
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R], \f[B]\[en]quiet\f[R]
Suppress per\-directory output.
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Removes empty directories under \f[CR]common/\f[R] and
\f[CR]profiles/<name>/\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Keeps structural directories such as \f[CR]common/\f[R],
\f[CR]profiles/\f[R], and profile roots
.IP \[bu] 2
Does not remove files or symlinks
.IP \[bu] 2
Runs automatically after \f[CR]tildr profile mv\f[R]
.SS tildr status
Shows the synchronization state of files effective for the active
profile.
.IP
.EX
tildr status
tildr status \-\-json
tildr status \-\-counter
tildr status \-\-less
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Output example:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
PROFILE     FILEPATH            STATUS
no profile  \[ti]/.zshrc            ✔ linked
no profile  \[ti]/Templates/main.sh  ✔ linked
linux       \[ti]/.bashrc           ✔ linked
.EE
.PP
The table output always includes the \f[CR]PROFILE\f[R] column.
Without \f[CR]\-\-profile\f[R], Tildr shows the effective variant for
each logical file.
By default \f[CR]FILEPATH\f[R] is the home\-relative path you can pass
to commands such as \f[CR]restore\f[R], \f[CR]unlink\f[R],
\f[CR]cat\f[R], and \f[CR]del\f[R]; use \f[CR]list \-\-source\f[R] or
\f[CR]source\-path\f[R] to inspect repository source files.
Shared files stored in \f[CR]common/\f[R] are shown as
\f[CR]no profile\f[R] in human\-readable tables.
.PP
\f[B]Options:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-j\f[R], \f[B]\[en]json\f[R]
Emit structured JSON output.
.TP
\f[B]\-c\f[R], \f[B]\[en]counter\f[R]
Print aggregated counters only.
.TP
\f[B]\-l\f[R], \f[B]\[en]less\f[R]
View the output in an interactive pager (uses \f[CR]$PAGER\f[R] or
\f[CR]less \-RFX\f[R]).
.PP
\f[B]Status values:\f[R]
.TP
\f[CR]linked\f[R]
Symlink exists and points to the correct repository file.
.TP
\f[CR]missing_link\f[R]
Repository file exists but the home symlink is absent.
.TP
\f[CR]broken_symlink\f[R]
A symlink exists but points to a wrong target.
.TP
\f[CR]not_a_symlink\f[R]
A regular file or directory exists where the symlink should be.
.PP
The \f[B]\[en]counter\f[R] mode prints a summary:
.IP
.EX
Managed: 12
Linked: 10
Missing: 1
Broken: 0
Not symlink: 1
.EE
