.SS tildr group
Manages named groups of managed files for batch operations.
.IP
.EX
tildr group list
tildr group create dev \-\-files .bashrc .config/nvim
tildr group add dev \-\-files .tmux.conf
tildr group add term \-\-files .term
tildr group rm dev \-\-files .tmux.conf
tildr group rm term \-\-files .term
tildr group rename dev shell
tildr group delete dev
tildr group apply dev
tildr group unlink dev
.EE
.PP
Groups store logical HOME\-relative paths.
Existing \f[CR]groups.json\f[R] entries using legacy \f[CR]common/\f[R],
\f[CR]profiles/<name>/\f[R], \f[CR]\[ti]\f[R], or \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] paths
are normalized when loaded and saved in logical form on the next group
mutation.
.PP
\f[B]Subcommands:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]create\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R] \f[B]\[en]files\f[R] \f[I]<FILES>\f[R]
Create a new group with the specified files or folders.
Folders are expanded recursively.
.TP
\f[B]add\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R] \f[B]\[en]files\f[R] \f[I]<FILES>\f[R]
Add files or folders to an existing group.
Folders are expanded recursively.
If no \f[CR]\-\-files\f[R] is provided, opens a file picker.
.TP
\f[B]rm\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R] \f[B]\[en]files\f[R] \f[I]<FILES>\f[R]
Remove files or folders from a group.
Folders remove all entries that start with that path recursively.
.TP
\f[B]rename\f[R] \f[I][<FROM>]\f[R] \f[I][<TO>]\f[R]
Rename a group.
Prompts for missing names and preserves the group\[cq]s file list.
.TP
\f[B]delete\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R]
Delete a group.
.TP
\f[B]list\f[R]
List all groups and their files.
.TP
\f[B]apply\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R]
Create symlinks for all files in the group.
.TP
\f[B]unlink\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R]
Remove symlinks for all files in the group.
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Groups are stored in \f[CR].tildr/groups.json\f[R] in the repository
root
.IP \[bu] 2
Groups store logical \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] paths, such as \f[CR].bashrc\f[R]
or \f[CR].config/nvim/init.lua\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]\-\-files\f[R] accepts \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] paths, \f[CR]\[ti]\f[R],
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R], cwd\-relative paths, \f[CR]common/<path>\f[R], and
\f[CR]profiles/<name>/<path>\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]\-\-files\f[R] accepts both files and folders; folders are
expanded recursively
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]add\f[R] with a folder adds all files inside it
(e.g.\ \f[CR]\-\-files .term\f[R] adds \f[CR].term/*.sh\f[R], etc.)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]rm\f[R] with a folder removes all entries that start with that
path (e.g.\ \f[CR]\-\-files .term\f[R] removes
\f[CR].term/behavior.sh\f[R], \f[CR].term/colors.sh\f[R], etc.)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]rename\f[R] preserves the group\[cq]s file list and only changes
the group name
.IP \[bu] 2
When no \f[CR]\-\-files\f[R] is provided, \f[CR]add\f[R] opens a file
picker in the repository
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]apply\f[R] creates symlinks in \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] for all files in
the group
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]unlink\f[R] removes symlinks from \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] for all files
in the group
.IP \[bu] 2
Group operations work on files already managed by Tildr
.SS tildr profile
Manages profile variants for machine\-specific dotfiles.
This is the main workflow for keeping one dotfiles repository while
switching between machines, distributions, jobs, or personal setups.
.PP
Files in \f[CR]common/\f[R] are shared everywhere and are addressed as
\f[CR]no\-profile\f[R] in profile commands.
A named profile such as \f[CR]linux\f[R], \f[CR]work\f[R], or
\f[CR]laptop\f[R] can override any no\-profile file.
When you run \f[CR]tildr profile set <name>\f[R], Tildr stores that
profile as active and immediately relinks \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] so matching
files point to \f[CR]profiles/<name>/\f[R], while everything else keeps
pointing to \f[CR]common/\f[R].
.IP
.EX
tildr profile create work \-\-description \[dq]Work environment\[dq]
tildr profile add no\-profile \-\-files .bashrc .ssh/config \-\-to work
tildr profile mv no\-profile \-\-to work                               \f[I]# move all no\-profile files to work\f[R]
tildr profile mv no\-profile \-f .bashrc \-\-to work                    \f[I]# move .bashrc to work\f[R]
tildr profile mv no\-profile \-f \[ti]/.xinitrc \-\-to work                 \f[I]# HOME paths are accepted\f[R]
tildr profile mv work \-\-to no\-profile                               \f[I]# restore all from work to no\-profile\f[R]
tildr profile add work \-f .bashrc \-\-to personal                     \f[I]# copy .bashrc between profiles\f[R]
tildr profile rename                                                \f[I]# interactive rename\f[R]
tildr profile rename linux archlinux \-\-description \[dq]Dotfiles Arch Linux\[dq]
tildr profile del work
tildr profile list
tildr profile list \-\-long
tildr profile list work \-\-long
tildr profile list \-\-less
tildr profile set work                                          \f[I]# activates and relinks $HOME\f[R]
tildr profile current
tildr profile unset                                             \f[I]# returns links to no\-profile files\f[R]
tildr profile migrate
tildr profile migrate \-\-dry\-run
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Subcommands:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]create\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R] \f[B][\[en]description\f[R] \f[I]<DESC>\f[R]\f[B]]\f[R]
Create a new profile using one path\-safe name.
\f[CR]\[dq]common\[dq]\f[R], \f[CR]\[dq]no\-profile\[dq]\f[R], and
\f[CR]\[dq]default\[dq]\f[R] are reserved and cannot be used as profile
names.
.TP
\f[B]add\f[R] \f[I]<FROM>\f[R] \f[B][\-f\f[R] \f[I]<FILES>\f[R]\f[B]] \[en]to\f[R] \f[I]<TO>\f[R]
Copy files between no\-profile files (\f[CR]no\-profile\f[R]), profiles,
or between profiles.
With no \f[CR]\-f\f[R], copies all eligible files from source (orphans
for \f[CR]no\-profile\f[R], all tracked files for a profile).
Folders are expanded recursively.
.TP
\f[B]mv\f[R] \f[I]<FROM>\f[R] \f[B][\-f\f[R] \f[I]<FILES>\f[R]\f[B]] \[en]to\f[R] \f[I]<TO>\f[R]
Move files between no\-profile files (\f[CR]no\-profile\f[R]), profiles,
or between profiles.
Same as \f[CR]add\f[R] but removes the source files.
Without \f[CR]\-f\f[R], moves all eligible files from source.
.TP
\f[B]del\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R]
Delete a profile entirely.
Removes it from \f[CR]profiles.json\f[R], deletes the
\f[CR]profiles/<name>/\f[R] directory, and restores orphaned files to
\f[CR]common/\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]rename\f[R] \f[I][<FROM>]\f[R] \f[I][<TO>]\f[R] \f[B][\[en]description** \f[BI]<DESC>\f[B]**]\f[R]
Rename a profile and optionally replace its description.
Prompts for missing names and description in interactive mode.
When \f[CR]\-\-description\f[R] is omitted in CLI mode, the existing
description is preserved.
If the profile is active, updates the active profile name.
.TP
\f[B]list\f[R]
List all available profiles.
.RS
.PP
\f[CR]\-\-long\f[R], \f[CR]\-l\f[R]
.RE
Show the files in each profile.
.RS
.PP
\f[CR]\-\-less\f[R]
.RE
Page the output through less.
.RS
.PP
\f[CR]<NAME>\f[R]
.RE
Show only the specified profile.
.PP
File arguments for \f[CR]profile add \-f\f[R] and
\f[CR]profile mv \-f\f[R] are logical HOME paths.
You can use \f[CR].bashrc\f[R], \f[CR]\[ti]/.bashrc\f[R],
\f[CR]$HOME/.bashrc\f[R], absolute paths inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R], paths
relative to your current directory when you are inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R],
or compatibility storage paths such as \f[CR]common/.bashrc\f[R] and
\f[CR]profiles/linux/.bashrc\f[R].
.PP
\f[CR]profile rename\f[R] can run fully interactively:
.IP
.EX
Enter current profile name:
Enter new profile name:
Enter description:
.EE
.TP
\f[B]set\f[R] \f[I]<NAME>\f[R]
Set the active profile and relink \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] immediately.
Stores the profile name in \f[CR].tildr/profiles.json\f[R].
Only one profile can be active at a time.
Setting a new profile replaces the previous one.
Matching files point to \f[CR]profiles/<name>/\f[R]; files without a
profile variant keep using \f[CR]common/\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]unset\f[R]
Unset the active profile and relink \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] to no\-profile
files.
Clears the \f[CR]active\f[R] field in \f[CR].tildr/profiles.json\f[R].
After unsetting, all files resolve to their no\-profile version when
available.
.TP
\f[B]current\f[R]
Show the currently active profile.
.TP
\f[B]migrate\f[R] \f[B][\[en]dry\-run]\f[R]
Move old repo\-root dotfiles into \f[CR]common/\f[R].
Use this for older repositories that still store dotfiles directly at
the repository root.
It preserves relative paths and does not move Tildr internals or
repository control files such as \f[CR].tildr/\f[R], \f[CR].git/\f[R],
\f[CR].github/\f[R], \f[CR].gitignore\f[R], \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R], or
\f[CR]profiles/\f[R].
Without \f[CR]\-\-dry\-run\f[R], performs the migration and commits.
With \f[CR]\-\-dry\-run\f[R], shows what would be moved without making
changes.
.PP
\f[B]Active Profile Behavior:\f[R]
.PP
The active profile is a per\-file override mechanism.
When \f[CR]tildr apply\f[R], \f[CR]tildr status\f[R], or
\f[CR]tildr doctor\f[R] processes a managed file, the resolution works
as follows:
.IP "1." 3
Check if the file has a variant in the active profile
.IP "2." 3
If yes, use the profile variant (\f[CR]profiles/<name>/<file>\f[R])
.IP "3." 3
If no, fall back to the no\-profile version (\f[CR]common/<file>\f[R])
.IP "4." 3
If no shared no\-profile version exists, fall back to legacy
\f[CR]profiles/common/<file>\f[R]
.IP "5." 3
If no legacy shared version exists, fall back to legacy
\f[CR]profiles/default/<file>\f[R] or root files
.PP
Files that exist only in an inactive named profile are not linked until
that profile is activated.
For every effective logical path, the active profile determines which
physical variant is used.
.PP
Example: if the active profile is \f[CR]work\f[R] and it tracks
\f[CR].bashrc\f[R] and \f[CR].ssh/config\f[R]:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]\[ti]/.bashrc\f[R] → \f[CR]profiles/work/.bashrc\f[R] (profile
variant)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]\[ti]/.ssh/config\f[R] → \f[CR]profiles/work/.ssh/config\f[R]
(profile variant)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]\[ti]/.gitconfig\f[R] → \f[CR]common/.gitconfig\f[R] (no\-profile
version, not in profile)
.PP
Switching profiles applies the new links right away:
.IP
.EX
tildr profile set work
\f[I]# \[ti]/.bashrc now points to profiles/work/.bashrc when that variant exists\f[R]

tildr profile set personal
\f[I]# \[ti]/.bashrc now points to profiles/personal/.bashrc when that variant exists\f[R]

tildr profile unset
\f[I]# \[ti]/.bashrc falls back to the no\-profile source at common/.bashrc\f[R]
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Migration:\f[R]
.PP
Use \f[CR]tildr profile migrate\f[R] when you have an older repository
with dotfiles at the repository root or in legacy
\f[CR]profiles/common/\f[R] and want to adopt the profile layout.
It moves shared dotfiles and directories into \f[CR]common/\f[R],
preserving their relative paths.
It does not move Tildr internals or repository control files such as
\f[CR].tildr/\f[R], \f[CR].git/\f[R], \f[CR].github/\f[R],
\f[CR].gitignore\f[R], \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R], or named profiles under
\f[CR]profiles/\f[R].
.PP
Preview the migration first:
.IP
.EX
tildr profile migrate \-\-dry\-run
.EE
.PP
Example dry\-run output:
.IP
.EX
  Would migrate: .bashrc \-> common/.bashrc
  Would migrate: .gitconfig \-> common/.gitconfig
  Would migrate: .config \-> common/.config
  Would migrate: profiles/common/.zshrc \-> common/.zshrc

Would migrate: 4 file(s) would be moved to common/ (dry run)
.EE
.PP
Then perform the migration:
.IP
.EX
tildr profile migrate
tildr profile list \-\-long
tildr status
.EE
.PP
Before:
.IP
.EX
\[ti]/.dotfiles/
  .bashrc
  .gitconfig
  .config/nvim/init.lua
  .tildr/
.EE
.PP
After:
.IP
.EX
\[ti]/.dotfiles/
  .tildr/
  common/
    .bashrc
    .gitconfig
    .config/nvim/init.lua
  profiles/
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Profiles are stored in \f[CR].tildr/profiles.json\f[R] in the repository
root
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]no\-profile\f[R] is the command argument for shared files stored
in \f[CR]common/\f[R]; \f[CR]common\f[R] remains accepted for
compatibility
.IP \[bu] 2
Legacy repositories with \f[CR]profiles/common/\f[R] are still supported
as a fallback
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]default\f[R] is only kept as a legacy compatibility fallback
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]add\f[R] copies files preserving the source; \f[CR]mv\f[R] moves
files atomically when possible
.IP \[bu] 2
Existing destination variants are skipped instead of overwritten
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]mv\f[R] removes empty source directories left after moving files
.IP \[bu] 2
Without \f[CR]\-f\f[R], \f[CR]add\f[R]/\f[CR]mv\f[R] operate on all
eligible files (orphans for \f[CR]no\-profile\f[R], all tracked files
for a profile)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]del\f[R] removes the profile directory and restores orphaned files
to \f[CR]common/\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]rename\f[R] supports empty profiles, renames the profile
directory, updates the active profile name, and immediately repairs
affected links
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]set\f[R] and \f[CR]unset\f[R] immediately relink \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
to the new effective profile
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]del\f[R] relinks \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] after deletion, so removed
active profiles fall back to no\-profile files
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]apply\f[R] can be run manually to repair or reapply links using
the active profile
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]status\f[R] uses the active profile to verify symlink targets
match the expected variant
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]doctor\f[R] uses the active profile to check symlink integrity
.IP \[bu] 2
Files not in the active profile fall back to the no\-profile version
.IP \[bu] 2
Only one profile can be active at a time
.IP \[bu] 2
Auto\-commits changes to the repository
.PP
\f[B]Example structure:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
common/
  .bashrc                            # no\-profile version
  .ssh/config                        # no\-profile SSH config
profiles/
  work/
    .bashrc                          # work variant
    .ssh/config                      # work SSH config
  personal/
    .bashrc                          # personal variant
.EE
.SS tildr secret
Manages encryption of sensitive files in your dotfiles repository using
GPG.
.IP
.EX
tildr secret add \[ti]/.ssh/id_rsa
tildr secret rm .ssh/id_rsa
tildr secret list
tildr secret encrypt
tildr secret decrypt
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Subcommands:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]add\f[R] \f[I]<FILE>\f[R]
Registers a file as sensitive, adds its actual profile source path to
\f[CR].gitignore\f[R], removes that source from Git tracking if already
tracked, and re\-encrypts the full bundle.
.TP
\f[B]rm\f[R] \f[I]<FILE>\f[R]
Unregisters a file from the manifest and re\-encrypts the bundle without
it.
Accepts logical, \f[CR]\[ti]\f[R], \f[CR]$HOME\f[R], absolute HOME, and
current\-directory paths.
If no files remain, the bundle is deleted.
The original file in \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] is not touched.
.TP
\f[B]list\f[R]
Lists all sensitive files currently registered in
\f[CR].tildr/encrypted\-items\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]encrypt\f[R]
Manually re\-encrypts all registered files into the bundle using their
current content from \f[CR]$HOME\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]decrypt\f[R]
Decrypts the bundle and restores all registered files to their original
locations in \f[CR]$HOME\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
GPG must be installed and available in \f[CR]PATH\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Two encryption modes are supported, configured via
\f[CR][crypto].mode\f[R] in \f[CR]config.toml\f[R]:
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]symmetric\f[R] (default) \[em] passphrase only, no key pair
required
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]asymmetric\f[R] \[em] uses an existing GPG key pair;
\f[CR][crypto].gpg_key\f[R] sets the recipient
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
In asymmetric mode, if \f[CR]gpg_key\f[R] is not set, Tildr prompts
interactively and saves the chosen key to config
.IP \[bu] 2
Sensitive sources may physically live under \f[CR]common/\f[R] or
\f[CR]profiles/<name>/\f[R], but they are ignored and removed from Git
tracking; only the encrypted bundle is committed
.IP \[bu] 2
Only the encrypted bundle \f[CR].tildr/encrypted.gpg\f[R] and the
plaintext manifest \f[CR].tildr/encrypted\-items\f[R] are committed
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]tildr sync\f[R] automatically re\-encrypts before pushing
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]tildr import\f[R] automatically decrypts after cloning if a bundle
is present
.IP \[bu] 2
Auto\-commits the repository when \f[CR]git.auto_commit = true\f[R]
.SS tildr sync
Synchronizes the repository with its configured Git remote in both
directions.
.IP
.EX
tildr sync
tildr sync \-\-dry\-run
tildr sync \-\-force
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Options:\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\[en]dry\-run\f[R]
Preview pull, merge, and push actions without executing.
.TP
\f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\[en]force\f[R]
Use \f[CR]\-\-force\-with\-lease\f[R] for the final \f[CR]git push\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R], \f[B]\[en]quiet\f[R]
Suppress output.
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Uses the current branch dynamically
.IP \[bu] 2
Uses the branch tracking remote and upstream branch from Git config
.IP \[bu] 2
Fetches from the tracked remote before deciding what to do
.IP \[bu] 2
If only local commits exist, pushes them
.IP \[bu] 2
If only remote commits exist, performs a fast\-forward pull
.IP \[bu] 2
If both local and remote commits exist, simulates a merge first
.IP \[bu] 2
Reapplies the effective profile after pulls and merges so new, moved, or
removed files are reconciled in \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Aborts safely and reports conflicting files when a merge conflict would
occur
.IP \[bu] 2
Uses the saved Git availability from Tildr config instead of probing
\f[CR]PATH\f[R] on every run
.IP \[bu] 2
Before pushing, re\-encrypts the secret bundle if sensitive files are
registered
.IP \[bu] 2
Skips re\-encryption when secret files are missing from \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
(warns instead of failing)
.SS tildr doctor
Runs a health check against the Tildr environment and reports any
issues.
.IP
.EX
tildr doctor
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Checks performed:\f[R]
.TP
Repository
Repository directory exists.
.TP
Config
Config file exists at expected path.
.TP
Git
Repository is a Git repo and the working tree has no pending or
untracked changes.
.TP
Permissions
Repository and managed files are accessible.
.TP
Disk
Repository total size on disk.
.TP
Symlinks
Effective active\-profile symlinks are correct; reports broken or
missing links.
.SS tildr completions
Generate shell completion scripts for various shells.
.IP
.EX
tildr completions bash
tildr completions zsh
tildr completions fish
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Argument:\f[R]
.PP
The shell to generate completions for: \f[CR]bash\f[R], \f[CR]zsh\f[R],
\f[CR]fish\f[R], \f[CR]powershell\f[R], or \f[CR]elvish\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]Installation:\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]Bash:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
tildr completions bash >> \[ti]/.bash_completion
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Zsh (Oh My Zsh):\f[R]
.IP
.EX
tildr completions zsh > \[ti]/.oh\-my\-zsh/completions/_tildr
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Zsh (vanilla):\f[R]
.PP
Add the following to \f[CR]\[ti]/.zshrc\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
fpath=(\[ti]/.zfunc $fpath)
autoload \-Uz compinit \f[B]&&\f[R] compinit
.EE
.PP
Then install completions:
.IP
.EX
tildr completions zsh > \[ti]/.zfunc/_tildr
.EE
.PP
Finally, restart your shell or run \f[CR]exec zsh\f[R] for changes to
take effect.
.PP
\f[B]Fish:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
tildr completions fish > \[ti]/.config/fish/completions/tildr.fish
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Behavior:\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Generates and outputs shell\-specific completion scripts
.IP \[bu] 2
No interactive installation \[em] output is printed to stdout for you to
redirect or pipe
.IP \[bu] 2
Each shell has its own completion script format and installation
location
.SS tildr info
Displays project metadata.
.IP
.EX
tildr info credits
tildr info license
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Modes:\f[R]
.TP
\f[CR]credits\f[R]
Build metadata, repository URL, license, commit hash, maintainer,
homepage.
.TP
\f[CR]license\f[R]
Installed license text, opened through a pager when available.
.SH INTERACTIVE BEHAVIOR
When a target is omitted, the following commands open an interactive
file picker over the list of managed files:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]add\f[R] (picks from \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] instead of the repository)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]cat\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]edit\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]unlink\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]restore\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]del\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]mv\f[R]
.PP
When the number of managed files exceeds
\f[CR]core.search_threshold\f[R] (default: \f[CR]15\f[R]), the picker
shows a search step first.
Type a fragment to filter the list by fuzzy match, or press enter with
an empty input to skip filtering and see the full list.
.SH TYPICAL WORKFLOW
Initial setup:
.IP
.EX
tildr init
tildr suggest
tildr add .bashrc
tildr add .config/nvim
tildr status
tildr doctor
tildr backup
.EE
.PP
Daily operations:
.IP
.EX
tildr apply
tildr status
tildr stats
tildr git status
tildr sync
.EE
.PP
Recovery and maintenance:
.IP
.EX
tildr status
tildr doctor
tildr apply
tildr unlink .config/nvim
tildr restore .bashrc
.EE
.PP
Secret file management:
.IP
.EX
tildr secret add \[ti]/.ssh/id_rsa
tildr secret list
tildr secret encrypt
tildr sync
.EE
.PP
Batch operations with groups:
.IP
.EX
tildr group create dev \-\-files .bashrc .zshrc .tmux.conf
tildr group add term \-\-files .term
tildr group apply dev
tildr group unlink dev
.EE
.SH OPERATIONAL NOTES
.IP \[bu] 2
Tildr is designed for home\-directory management on Linux and macOS
.IP \[bu] 2
The repository must stay inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Relative paths for managed targets are interpreted from
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R], or from the current directory when you are inside
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R] and the path matches there
.IP \[bu] 2
Directory operations are recursive over all files under that path
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]apply\f[R] does not overwrite conflicting regular files unless
\f[CR]\-\-force\f[R] is provided
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]unlink\f[R] removes only symlinks, never repository content
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]restore\f[R] physically moves the real file back out of the
repository
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]del\f[R] removes repository content; use \f[CR]\-\-purge\f[R] for
permanent deletion
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]git.auto_commit\f[R] affects \f[CR]add\f[R], \f[CR]restore\f[R],
\f[CR]del\f[R], \f[CR]mv\f[R], \f[CR]secret\f[R], \f[CR]exclude\f[R],
\f[CR]group\f[R], and \f[CR]profile\f[R] \[em] not \f[CR]apply\f[R],
\f[CR]unlink\f[R], \f[CR]git\f[R], or \f[CR]sync\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]git.enable = false\f[R] disables Tildr\-managed Git operations
even if Git is installed
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]tildr secret\f[R] requires \f[CR]gpg\f[R] to be installed and
available in \f[CR]PATH\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Sensitive files registered with \f[CR]tildr secret add\f[R] are removed
from Git tracking; only the encrypted bundle is committed
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]core.color = false\f[R] in \f[CR]config.toml\f[R] disables all
colored output; the \f[CR]NO_COLOR\f[R] environment variable is also
respected
.IP \[bu] 2
The \f[CR]\-\-less\f[R] flag is available on \f[CR]tildr status\f[R],
\f[CR]tildr list\f[R], and \f[CR]tildr cat\f[R] for interactive pager
output
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR].tildrignore\f[R] patterns prevent files from being discovered by
\f[CR]list\f[R], \f[CR]status\f[R], and \f[CR]apply\f[R]
.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
.TP
\f[B]EDITOR\f[R]
Editor used by \f[CR]tildr edit\f[R].
Falls back to \f[CR]$VISUAL\f[R], then \f[CR]nano\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]VISUAL\f[R]
Alternative editor used by \f[CR]tildr edit\f[R] if \f[CR]$EDITOR\f[R]
is not set.
.TP
\f[B]PAGER\f[R]
Pager used by \f[CR]tildr cat \-\-less\f[R] and
\f[CR]tildr status \-\-less\f[R].
Falls back to \f[CR]less \-RFX\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
When set, disables all colored output regardless of
\f[CR]core.color\f[R] config.
